remarks: Severity is high for juvenile PSMEM (~8-18 years), low for majority of mature and seedling boles, with some exceptional individuals. Swiss Needle Cast. Chlorosis and needle loss of 2-4th year growth, as well as ascomata observed on PSMEM throughout the site. Young stands (planted ~2000-2012) are most obviously affected, in some cases > 95% of individuals indicating and >50% retaining <2nd year growth. Rarely, mature trees observed with <2nd year growth.

ABBY_007 (distributed base) and ABBY_033 (mosquito point) are located 100% within the expected spray area. ABBY_007 (mammal grid) is located >50% within the spray area and partially within a riparian buffer zone that was not harvested and likely not sprayed. The \'Havarti Sorts\' harvest unit was sprayed via helicopter on July 14, 2017. According to a posted sign, the chemicals were: \'Rodeo\' (EPA Reg. No. 62719-324), \'Chopper Gen 2\' (EPA Reg. No. 241-430), and \'Dust Extra\' (EPA Reg. No. 432-1552). The Havarti Sorts harvest unit was sprayed aerially on July 14, 2017.

Disturbed soil and vegetation along tick drag path. Soil sampling pit dug in incorrect plot by contractors. Vegetation also trampled/matted down in vicinity. Contractors mistakenly dug a soil pit at the ABBY_001 tick plot rather than the ABBY_001 base plot. This happened no earlier than 2017-07-17 and no later than 2017-07-19. NEON field technicians discovered the disturbance while sampling for ticks ABBY_001 for ticks on 2017-07-19. The soil pit location was along or adjacent to the tick drag path.

Posted sign identified the chemicals used as Garlon 3a (EPA Registration No. 62719-037) and Roundup Pro (EPA Registration No. 524-529). Posted signs announced herbicide application along state forest road L-1070 and spurs. Specified plots are located along this road and may have been sprayed.

Chemicals used not recorded by sampling crew. Mosquito sampling crew discovered that roadside herbicide application had occurred between September 7, 2017 morning and evening collections. ABBY_031 is located along the affected road and may have been sprayed.

remarks: COCOC, FRPU7, ALRU2, under performing and heavily diseased PSMEM. Biomass discarded in situ. Management activities reduced competition by removing hardwoods, mainly COCOC, FRPU7 and ALRU2, as well as under performing and diseased (Phaeocryptopus gaeumannii) PSMEM. These activities were conducted throughout the airshed entire plot area is affected.

Trees were cut and left in place within and around all soil plots at ABBY, both coniferous (PSMEM) and deciduous (ALRU2, FRPU7, COCOC) individuals. This thinning appears to be prescribed as part of the stand management regime in place by our site host. No instrument were damaged in the process.

A fish sampling event was conducted by an external researcher. Each site (12 total) of 100 m was sampled by two passes of a single backpack electroshocker and a third pass by a combination of seine and shocker. Dip nets used for mosquitofish in the backwater habitat. Only one of the sample locations was located within our permitted reach and was approx. 300 meters downstream of S2 sensor set.
6/5/2019 Beaver dam built overnight. We left the stream at 6pm and it was not there. Upon arrival @ 9am it was here. 6/11/2019 The dam has grown since the above date and attached is another photo.

Cows were seen around sensor set 2 on 11/04/2019. Unsure of exact dates that the cows entered and exited the stream reach. A salt block and watering hole were set up near sensor set 2 around this time.

Had arborist cut down tree from tower guy wire. Tree was left on ground where it fell to decay naturally.

Two dead tree stems fell on the throughfall collector in BART SP1. We removed the stems and set them down on the ground next to the throughfall collector. This may have happened during a storm on May 4 2018. We visited the site on May 2 and there were no trees on the throughfall collector and we returned on May 14 and the trees were on the sensor. The throughfall collector was not level and the base was bent so we removed it until we get a replacement. Dead trees landed on sensor.

A tree had fallen across the BART soil plot 4, but was suspended over the sensors, not touching them. Arborists climbed trees and used rigging to gently lower the broken bole down to the snow on the ground and cut the stem into logs and moved them just out of the soil plot. There was 15-30 cm of snow on the ground and the arborists are certain that the tree didn't touch the CO2 sensor housings or other sensors, but since they couldn't see sensors below the snow they removed the stem from the plot so the tree wouldn't land on snow-buried sensors when the snow melts in the spring.

locationID: BIGC.AOS.discharge, S2LOC111034, CFGLOC111036, CFGLOC113856, CFGLOC111037, CFGLOC113857, CFGLOC111035, CFGLOC111038
dateRemarks: The latest start date is 2020-04-05. The earliest end date is 2020-04-06.
remarks: Storm and subsequent 'flooding' occurred from 04/05/20 ~1800 UTC through 04/06/20 ~ 2000 UTC. Sensors remained buried until 6/16/2020 when we regained field access. Crew was not able to assess potential flood impacts at other AOS locations (i.e. plant transects) due to COVID.

remarks: Precipitation over the Blue River Watershed on 20191030 caused discharge to increase from an estimated 5,663 lps to an estimated 14,158 lps on 20191030 and 20191031. Discharge dropped below an estimated 5,663 lps by 20191102. Estimations are based on USGS Monitoring gage 07332390 which is located downstream from the permitted reach boundary.

On November 12, 2019, from 16:25 GMT to 16:55 GMT, while preparing to conduct a discharge measurement using the Acoustic Doppler Current Profiler (ADCP) I deconstructed a portion of an obstruction located downstream of the sensor set and known to influence hydrologic conditions within the discharge and sensor reach to reduce side channel flow which would not have been recorded along the discharge transect. This disturbance resulted in a measured change in surface water elevation of 0.0365 meters, which is the difference between the initial elevation of 289.0071 and the final elevation of 288.9706.

Partial Dam Removal

dateRemarks: start date is estimated but end date is actual date
remarks: a dead beaver was found stuck to the upstream side of the buoy location. It is not sure how long it was there but judging by the level of decomposition when we saw it, it could've been there the whole weekend. pictures were taken after it was pushed off the buoy
The snow on the top of the ridge was too deep to reach the last two MOS points - Bouts 1-3 we were only able to sample 8/10 MOS points.

dateRemarks: Fire first reported on listed date.
remarks: This week we saw the Haystack fire exploded which reportedly started as Fire 163 that we first reported on June 7th. It seemed to smolder underground for several days, and on June 14th conditions were suitable for it to ignite above-ground foliage. Over the past several days the fire has continued to spread, moving east through mostly spruce and tracking around a deciduous stand which is characteristic of boreal systems. Flame retardant (unknown quantity) was dropped on site and bulldozers constructed fire break lines - both of which could have impacted plots. No plots were directly burned.

dateRemarks: Wildfires burning across state of Alaska starting at beginning of June. Significant and consistent smoke accumulation in interior Alaska after June 15.
remarks: Smoke from multiple fires across interior Alaska is accumulating and impacting all D19 tower airsheds and gas analysis. No specific fire near site boundary.

dateRemarks: Start is fire discovery date.
remarks: See INC0067660 for sampling impacts

dateRemarks: Fire first reported on listed date.
remarks: This week we saw the Haystack fire exploded which reportedly started as Fire 163 that we first reported on June 7th. It seemed to smolder underground for several days, and on June 14th conditions were suitable for it to ignite above-ground foliage. Over the past several days the fire has continued to spread, moving east through mostly spruce and tracking around a deciduous stand which is characteristic of boreal systems. The Haystack fire is located almost entirely within the Caribou Creek watershed. Flame retardant (unknown quantity) was dropped in the watershed at the head of Caribou Creek and bulldozers constructed fire break lines - both of which will likely impact water quality. No plots were directly burned.

name: University of Colorado Mountain Research Station, US Forest Service
remarks: Point of contact on site. baseline reporting of land ownership

Research outside of NEON protocols being conducted on the downstream portion of the permitted reach, starting at Lat 40. 033183, Long -105. 541317. There are PVC wells (1-3x) installed on the stream bank at most of the 50 m intervals. There are electrode lines for electrical resistivity imaging setup at the 50 m and 350 m transects.

High discharge and snow melt. Snow melt is creating a few small and large tributaries that are adding additional water between S1 and S2. There are a couple more smaller ones besides these four as well.
The sensor infrastructure is vibrating due to high flow at the creek. This is causing the whole unistrut to shake and is making the PAR on both sensor sets to become unlevel.
There is external research infrastructure installed slightly above stream of plant transects 3 and 5 at COMO.

High discharge and snow melt. Snow melt is creating a few small and large tributaries that are adding additional water between S1 and S2. There are a couple more smaller ones besides these four as well.

High discharge and snow melt. Snow melt is creating a few small and large tributaries that are adding additional water between S1 and S2. There are a couple more smaller ones besides these four as well.

Throughout August and September a researcher will be adding salt slugs and constant-rate salt injections to the creek about once a week. This will be happening just below the wetland near C1 to the MRS weir.

Hurricane Idalia's eye came ashore in Florida's Big Bend region near Keaton Beach, Florida at 7:45 am on August 30, 2023 with sustained peak winds of 125 mph, as a hurricane category 3. At peak, the Hurricane was a category 4 hurricane. Outer bands as the eye was still in the Gulf of Mexico hit Disney Wilderness Preserve on Tuesday, august 29, afternoon and evening. The eye and strongest gusts of wind traveled north of Disney Wilderness Preserve. Highest projected gusts in Polk and Osceola county which is where the Preserve was located was around 40 mph and 2-3 inches of rain.

remarks: Subtropical Storm Alberto caused heavy rain fall, high flow, and flooding of the the Flint River starting 5/25. On 5/30 before conducting an AIS bout, we observed that the buoy had moved approximately 15 to 20 meters downstream of anchored location.
1 meter area around GWW cleared in preparation for controlled burn

dateRemarks: During BioBout sampling on 7/6/2022, we heard activity onshore and found the road along the river and by the AIS infrastructure to have been worked on.
remarks: A large pot hole in the area of the road just north of the met station and S1 was filled in, but in the process much of the vegetation around the road was removed. The road width in this area was almost doubled by the construction in the area near Riparian marker 3, and it is likely that at a part of RIP 3 plot was impacted.

dateRemarks: Heard the machinery and saw some of the progress while on the river during Bio Bout
remarks: Road widened and repaired for roughly 50 m with lots of indiscriminate bulldozing. A large pot hole in the area of the road just north of the met station and S1 was filled in, but in the process much of the vegetation around the road was removed. The road width in this area was almost doubled by the construction in the area near Riparian marker 3, and it is likely that at a part of RIP 3 plot was impacted.

They attempted to burn the low area near the Flint River. It was wet and the fire generally didn't run very far. Some places it went 3-4 m and others it did not burn anything beyond what the drip torch hit. Well 3 is still broken, and GWW4-7 were burned nearby but not directly adjacent ( across the road or a few square meters or less around those wells.

dateRemarks: We performed the removal
remarks: Clearing around instrumentation in preparation for a controlled burn

Gypsy moths defoliated oak-dominated stands in the Quabbin. gypsy moth. Gypsy moths defoliated upland oak-dominated forest stands. In mid-July the insects started to succumb to Entomophaga maimaiga and were seen in great numbers hanging dead from tree trunks.

dateRemarks: These plots had infrequent visits during the period of logging. The site hosts hired loggers who had very little understanding of where our plots were located, so we do not have accurate dates of logging.
remarks: The logging targeted large dead oaks killed by the drought and gypsy moth outbreak of 2016, and the logs left on the ground are mostly the ~15 cm diameter branches left behind by the loggers. In some areas there were multiple layers of these hardwood logs. HARV_018_R: We estimated that the logging affected 63% of the 40m x 40m plot, and nearly the entire 20m x 20 m plot. Only logs and ferns (mostly Dennstaedtia punctilobula) remain in these areas. From what the plot looks like now, and what remains of the canopy, I would classify it as a deciduous forest. HARV_012_R : more than 50% of the plot was logged. The area is now covered by ferns and tree seedlings, but many of them are Pinus strobus seedlings. Since the oaks were targeted for removal, I believe the classification of HARV_012_R should change to mixed forest. About 30% of HARV_004_R was logged in late 2019-early 2020. The logged area is currently dominated by ferns, but it includes tree seedlings.

remarks: Newly constructed boardwalk within HEAL_070 and HEAL_048 to reduce trampling. The boardwalk follows the southern cardinal direction outside of the 20x20 of HEAL_048 and follows all cardinal directions within HEAL_070 (see photos).

dateRemarks: Wildfires burning across state of Alaska starting at beginning of June. Significant and consistent smoke accumulation in interior Alaska after June 15.
remarks: Smoke from multiple fires across interior Alaska is accumulating and impacting all D19 tower airsheds and gas analysis. No specific fire near site boundary.

dateRemarks: The latest start date is 2020-04-19.
remarks: With the stay home order in Massachusetts people have been visiting trails at a higher frequency. The gravel roads around HOPB see relatively low visitation and it's unusual to see photos from the PhenoCam with people in them. During some nice weather on 20200419-20200420 the PhenoCam captured 3 different parties of individuals at the S2 location. They must have followed our well-used path that has been established from the road (where we have an informational sign) down to S2. Based on remote monitoring it doesn't look like anyone disturbed any instrumentation but it was thought important to document the uptick in visitation.

Beaver dams appeared some time between 8/9/22 and 10/3/22.
remarks: During the fall bio bout I discovered two beaver dams near the upstream end of the reach. The dams were observed on 10/3/22 and must have been constructed between 8/8/22 (last time we walked this stretch of the reach) and this latter date. The upper beaver dam is just downstream of the culvert scour pool (the road-crossing is the upstream end of the reach). Approximately 100m downstream is the second beaver dam, which at the time was only partially constructed. There has been a series of beaver dams upstream of the road-crossing since likely before the establishment of HOPB as a NEON site. However, dams have not been observed downstream of the culvert since site establishment. It is unknown as to how this will affect the hydrology or water chemistry at the site but we will be monitoring for obvious changes.

dateRemarks: Date is the first day that the drought impacted sampling schedule.
remarks: On 20220809 the MA Energy and Environmental Affairs Secretary announced that Franklin County was in Level 3-Critical Drought. I have observed extremely low flows and stage heights (0.135m on 20220817) at HOPB for the last few weeks. It has gotten to the point that completing discharge measurements is not feasible. The DSC-16 bout originally scheduled for 20220817 was cancelled due to this. Please see INC0058024. On 20221007 the MA Energy and Environmental Affairs Secretary upgraded Franklin County to Level 1-Mild Drought.

Hurricane Idalia's eye came ashore in Florida's Big Bend region near Keaton Beach, Florida at 7:45 am on August 30, 2023 with sustained peak winds of 125 mph, as a hurricane category 3. At peak, the Hurricane was a category 4 hurricane. Outer bands as the eye was still in the Gulf of Mexico hit Disney Wilderness Preserve on Tuesday, august 29, afternoon and evening. The eye and strongest gusts of wind traveled north of Disney Wilderness Preserve. Highest projected gusts in Polk and Osceola county which is where the Preserve was located was around 40 mph and 2-3 inches of rain.

dateRemarks: The latest start date is 2019-08-10.
remarks: Monsoon 2019 has been abysmal. Record dry conditions were reported throughout Arizona. This resulted in noticeably lower plant presence and cover when compared to previous years during our largest peak green plant diversity bout. Late season precipitation from tropical storms has helped on the ground conditions, but seasonal totals are still well below average. United States Drought Monitor used for approximate dates.

Site Host ag practices and NEON TIS ag replication events at KO from summer of 2017 through spring of 2018 are listed below. Subsequent events will be recorded separately as they occur. Week of 19 Jun 2017 approx- Site hosts harvested the wheat that was growing in the field. 7 to 14 July 2017: NEON TIS harvested the wheat around NEON infrastructure. 18 Jul 2017: Site hosts harvested additional wheat in areas between the soil plots. 1 Aug 2017: Site hosts disked the field. 15 Aug: Site hosts sprayed the field with mix of Roundup and Base Camp 2,4-D Amine. 20 Sep 2017: Site hosts disked the field. 22 Sep 2017: NEON TIS sprayed the field with same mix of chemicals. 24 Oct 2017: NEON TIS roto-tilled the field on 24 Oct 2017. 29 Nov 2017: Site hosts sprayed the field with Buccaneer Plus (glyphosate) and BaseCamp LV6 (2,4-D). NEON TIS did not spray between the plots, tower, and hut due to time and resource constraints. 10 Apr 2018: Site hosts sprayed fertilizer. NEON TIS did not apply additional fertilizer due to probable good coverage around and between the infrastructure. 4 April 2018: Site hosts tilled the field. 5 April 2018: NEON TIS roto-tilled the areas between and around the soil plots and infrastructure. 18-19 Apr 2018: Site hosts planted corn. 23 April 2018: NEON TIS planted corn manually in the areas that could not be planted by the site hosts.

photos to document crop growth around TIS infrastructure

On 17 Sept 2018 we cut the corn growing in and immediately around the soil plots, tower, hut, and phenology camera staff gauges. We placed the stalks vertically in the surrounding uncut corn where it can be processed by the site host's combine when he harvests the field within the next few days. We will then rack residue back into the areas which we cut ahead of time.

locationID: KONA, SOILPL102390, SOILPL102419, SOILPL102446, SOILPL102479, SOILPL102506, TOWER102356, HUT110625, AIRSHED
remarks: Site host harvested the corn crop at the KO site on 27 and 28 Sept 2018. On 2 Oct 2018 TIS techs gathered crop residue from the field and distributed it over the areas in and between the soil plots, the tower, the hut, the phenocam stakes, etc to replicate the conditions in the remainder of the field following completion of the site host's harvest.

Extensive frost heaving occurred in the sensor soil plots throughout Feb and first part of March due to deeply frozen ground and periodic rainfall and melting events. Frost heaving also visible throughout other parts of the tower field as indicated by raised portions of earth separated from surrounding soil by cracks.

dateRemarks: Start date is when the wildfire is estimated to have reached McRae Creek's downstream area.
remarks: A lightning-caused wildfire ignited on August 5, 2023, four miles NE of McKenzie Bridge, OR, was later named the Lookout Fire and resulted in substantial firefighting response. The size would reach 25,754 acres. https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident-information/orwif-lookout-fire The fire burned large areas of the forest in Lookout Creek's watershed, of which McRae Creek (MCRA) is a sub-watershed. The fire approached the McRae watershed from the south and appears to have burned the forest around the lower creek, from its confluence with Lookout Creek and reaching the study reach around August 27. However, a road (NF 325) about 200 m to the southeast of the creek, near where MCRA infrastructure is located and is the access road for the study reach, appears to have acted as a fire break. On October 10, the fire was reported to be 100% contained, with cooler weather and rain events providing fire-suppressing conditions. As of October 19, the extent and severity of impact to the study reach is unknown and the experimental forest remains closed to entry by NEON staff. The site lost power on October 20, presumably due to empty fuel, and staff is currently coordinating fuel delivery and will attempt to remotely restart the generation equipment. Published reports from the USFS Burned Area Emergency Response Team show the study reach area experienced low severity soil burn and 0-50% basal area mortality.

dateRemarks: Observations of needle browning were first recorded on 20230112 during phenology bout.
remarks: Emerging needles were reported for some Pinus palustrus during the phenology bout on 20221229. During subsequent bouts on 20230112 and 20230118 the buds and young needles had begun to turn brown and die. An internet search showed that our trees resembled those infected by a fungal pathogen possibly 'Tip Blight' Diplodia sapinea (https://hgic.clemson.edu/factsheet/pine-diseases/). This disease has the potential to impact several TOS protocols including Canopy Foliage; Litter; Vegetation Structure; and Phenology. This event is being recorded as Other (instead of Population Spike-pathogen) until confirmation from the OSBS site-host can be obtained regarding the cause of the browning/die-back. It is also unknown at this time whether the event will spread across the site.

Hurricane Idalia's eye came ashore in Florida's Big Bend region near Keaton Beach, Florida at 7:45 am on August 30, 2023 with sustained peak winds of 125 mph, as a hurricane category 3. At peak, the Hurricane was a category 4 hurricane. Outer bands as the eye was still in the Gulf of Mexico hit Disney Wilderness Preserve on Tuesday, august 29, afternoon and evening. The eye and strongest gusts of wind traveled north of Disney Wilderness Preserve. Highest projected gusts in Polk and Osceola county which is where the Preserve was located was around 40 mph and 2-3 inches of rain.

dateRemarks: The latest start date is 2019-04-23.
remarks: Evidence of damage to plants by machete along a trail through the plot. Likely done by pig hunters (also evidence of dog paw prints). Damage was on a trail to the plot and out through the plot. Most of the damage was to the ubiquitous tree free fern Cibotium glaucum but also included damage to Cyrtandra platyphylla. No photos taken

a 1000 acre ungulate-proof fence exclosure was recently constructed in the PUUM and it encapsulates PUUM_015 and PUUM_016. There are one-way gates along the fence to allow for animals to leave the exclosure and not return. This will increase the feral pig (Sus scrofa) presence in PUUM_004, PUUM_007, and PUUM_019, and eliminate feral pig disturbance in PUUM_015 and PUUM_016.

A phenology individual Styphelia tamiameiae with tagID 6045 was recently damaged. The cause of the damage is likely due to human disturbance (a construction crew has been replacing the nearby fence). According to the phenology annual measurements on 2/12/19, the plant was . 8 m in height. Measurements were not taken upon discovery of the incident but I would estimate it is less than . 5 m height now.
Buried or carried away, likely by feral pigs. subplot 031 SW corner lost. Spot where monument should be is heavily disturbed by feral pigs. Rebar is likely buried or has been moved.

Hazardous volcanic Sulfur Dioxide from nearby volcanic eruption. Concentration measured in parts per million. Volcanic gas plume direction and concentration are dependent on wind speed, wind direction, and level of volcanic activity.

remarks: Individuals of an endangered plant species (Cyanea shipmanii) have been outplanted within the boundaries of PUUM_031. Plants have since been removed from the plot.

remarks: In 2020, Utah Division of Wildlife Resources reported that 102 Bonneville Cutthroat Trout, 6 inches in length on average, were stocked in Red Butte Reservoir on June 15. The Red Butte Reservoir is downstream of the entire research reach. More information can be found at https://dwrapps.utah.gov/fishstocking/Fish.

In 2020, Utah Division of Wildlife Resources reported that 2001 Bonneville Cutthroat Trout, 2.27 inches in length on average, were stocked in Red Butte Reservoir on October 12th. The Red Butte Reservoir is downstream of the entire research reach. More information can be found at https://dwrapps.utah.gov/fishstocking/Fish.

In 2021, Utah Division of Wildlife Resources reported that 1646 Bonneville Cutthroat Trout, 2.43 inches in length on average, were stocked in Red Butte Reservoir on October 13th. 833 Bonneville Cutthroat Trout 2.43 inches in length on average were stocked in Red Butte Creek. The Red Butte Reservoir is downstream of the entire research reach. More information can be found at https://dwrapps.utah.gov/fishstocking/Fish.

In 2022, Utah Division of Wildlife Resources reported that 50 Bonneville Cutthroat Trout, 6.22 inches in length on average, were stocked in Red Butte Creek on June 8th. More information can be found at https://dwrapps.utah.gov/fishstocking/Fish.

In 2022, Utah Division of Wildlife Resources reported that 2331 Bonneville Cutthroat Trout, 2.09 inches in length on average, were stocked in Red Butte Reservoir on September 21st. A quantity of 1669 Bonneville Cutthroat Trout, 2.3 inches in length on average were also stocked in Red Butte Creek on September 21st. The Red Butte Reservoir is downstream of the entire research reach. More information can be found at https://dwrapps.utah.gov/fishstocking/Fish.

dateRemarks: Unsure when cloud seeding operation began
remarks: Cloud Seeding Operation taking place across Left Hand Canyon Area From site host : The cloud seeding project has already begun and they have done it a couple times. They focus on storms that are moving east to west (ie upslope) and the focus area is the Left Hand Canyon area which leads them directly to Wild Basin area of the park along with your Allenspark site and the Leiffer Property. They are hoping for a 1% - 10% or more increase in precipitation to support water volume. This could change some of the data you all collect in some ways. https://www.9news.com/article/weather/cloud-seeding-boulder-county/73-91bf9436-068b-4da4-867c-ab708c6b8bef

The San Joaquin Experimental Range harbors an ecosystem entirely dependent on fall/winter rains. The site hasn't experienced precipitation since June. New growth is triggered by the break in dry weather, and we have not experienced said break yet. The drought is interfering with the first bout of HBP and we intend to hold off on sampling until after the first rain event of the season.

remarks: Areas west and upslope of plot SOAP_002 R (including SOAP_002M and SOAP_006M were burned down to bare soil in the 2020 Creek fire. Vegetation did not regenerate and stabilize the slopes until spring of 2022. This lead to minor flash flooding in the ephemeral creek beds in 2021, and fast moving water deposited a layer of stream sediment in plot SOAP_002 R, primarily in subplots 21 and 39. As of 2022, vegetation is regrowing over the sediment in the flood channels.

The Blue Fire incident started on 6/30/2021 in the middle of Soaproot Saddle (SOAP) just east of the tower. Power was lost to the site so all instrumentation was down for some time. On 7/12/2021, while the site was still without power, we discovered a tree had fallen on the line PAR sensor in soil plot 5. Site power was restored around 7/22/2021. A section of the tree around the line PAR was cut and removed on 8/25/2021 in order to ensure the sensor was not damaged and to allow for necessary maintenance. The slice was placed nearby. This event may impact the Quantum Line Photosynthetically Active Radiation data products for this soil plot for the time period the tree was over the sensor, and potentially change the time series data going forward as the remaining trunk of the tree was left in place which may change the amount of light reaching the sensor compared to before.

Small fire on southern side of SRER

Moderate drought conditions persisting across all of southern Arizona, including SRER. Following a very wet monsoon and October and southeast Arizona, the drought conditions have subsided. Abnormally dry conditions persist throughout much of the region, but vegetation and soil indices indicate the worst of the drought is over. If winter rains fail to show up, D14 will create a new record documenting drought conditions for 2019.

remarks: Monsoon 2019 has been abysmal. Record dry conditions were reported throughout Arizona. This resulted in noticeably lower plant presence and cover when compared to previous years during our largest peak green plant diversity bout. Late season precipitation from tropical storms has helped on the ground conditions, but seasonal totals are still well below average. United States Drought Monitor used for approximate start dates.

Plot has apparently been wet in the past (according to returning staff) but not to the current extent.

Spring time flood water was reported to be nearly chest-deep on the outermost row of the bird grid. Deep flooding was reported on bird grid STEI_033. Report was made by contracted bird technicians so details are limited. Technician reported that springtime flooding created dangerous conditions on the grid and that water that was nearly chest-deep had to be waded to complete the grid. While there quantitative measures of this flooding are lacking, it seems to be more than typical for this time of year so it is being reported.

Large trees were blown over during a storm event on 8/5/19, opening up the canopy significantly in places. The disturbance was observed near mosquito point STEI_037 but elsewhere across the site may have been affected as well.

dateRemarks: Kestrel visited the site a few times over the course of 3 weeks. The date range represents the first and last visit recorded.
name: Kestrel
remarks: Coral Ardisia targeted, opportunistically targeted sword fern and Camphor.
Vegetation mat was blocking boat ramp exit. Enough of the mat was removed to make a clear path to the lake.

dateRemarks: Done between 1530 and 1700 on 20230413
remarks: Floating plants Limnobium and Hydrocotyle sp. moved from boat ramp to other side of barriers creating a less green phenocam image. Area thinned was roughly 3m x10m. Biomass was not removed from the lake, it was merely relocated to the other side of the barrier. Camera is not an option in the AIS impacted location dropdown above.
Floating plants Limnobium and Hydrocotyle were tossed over the barrier at the boat ramp to facilitate access. Only impacted location is the Phenocam that is not listed as an AIS location impacted
Boat ramp cleared by removing floating mats of Limnobium spongia.
Oak tree branches were trimmed directly adjacent to GWW6, and several whole trees were cut down about 50ft away from the well.

Evidence of cattle in stream.

dateRemarks: The latest start date is 2018-04-07. The earliest end date is 2018-03-29.
remarks: Rocks hit comm box and other cabling infrastructure along the cliff wall at S1. No obvious damage to equipment. 4th rock slide since install at site.
Conduit break at two new points between S1 and S2 at SYCA. Likely occurred due to rock slide. No damage to wiring or sensors.
Approximately 50 cows on site. Rancher said they arrived 20181022.
Rock slide in area of S2 heard while working at groundwater wells. No known damage to infrastructure at this point in time. Will investigate more during site visit scheduled next week.

dateRemarks: The latest start date is 2020-06-13. The earliest end date is 2020-06-29.
remarks: The Bush Fire started along Highway 87 on June 13th, 2020. On June 15th, 2020, the fire spread north along the highway, and into the area of Sycamore Creek watershed above and to the east of the site. Fire is likely to impact site either directly burning the site, having fire retardant dropped on the site, or will be indirectly impacted once ash and debris moves into the site with a storm event. https://inciweb.nwcg.gov/incident/6773/# Update as of 20200618 at 10AM local time, fire is ~115,000 acres. Fire hasn't burned the site, and a line is being maintained just west of the site along state highway 87. As of 20200701, the fire is 98% contained and is only burning within the secured perimeter of the fire. The total acreage is 193,455 acres. SYCA was not burned. Reports of water being used from nearby pond to help control fire over the past few weeks. While we have not been to the site to confirm any impact, we are assuming no areas at the site were impacted by the fire. Once staff return to site, another record will be made if impacts occurred.

remarks: Large flood on 8/12/2021. Downstream USGS gauge came in at 7,540 cfs at 6:00 MST. Flow dropped back down under 100 cfs by 23:50 MST that same day. The flood scoured out below S2 leaving them nearly all out of the water. Additionally, the cables to the SONDE and LevelTroll at S1 were ripped apart and the PRT at S1 was snapped in half.

remarks: A large flood moved through the site on 8/18/2021. The downstream USGS gauge peaked at 8,250 cfs at 17:30 MST. This was the largest flood event seen at SYCA since site establishment in 2017. Large woody debris moved across the site, knocking down vegetation, and depositing in new locations throughout the site. Large amounts of sediment (1 meter+) deposited in certain locations, while banks gave way, scouring and and widened the channel in other locations. Main channel flow also shifted 15 meters in some stretches of the site. Little vegetation remains at the site. Boulders the size of small vehicles, previously located between S1 and S2 are now gone.

remarks: External researchers from Arizona State University were onsite this past week (20220214) reinstalling their sensor housing which in near our S1 sensor location. See photo for image of infrastructure. To install the housing, they had tom move around some sediment in the area. They plan to return to install the sensors in the near future.

dateRemarks: Observed motorcycle tracks on 20220308 and they were not there during last visit on 20220303.
remarks: Motorcycle drove through site. Tracks observed from top down past S1. Did not observe downstream because all work was near top.

Observations of this invasive plant have drastically increased in recent weeks. The first sighting was in 2019, and now the plant has spread across much of the site in open areas, along the stream banks, and is heavily present on the access/parking area for NEON.

dateRemarks: Unsure of actual date of fire. Noticed burn scar between site visits, and narrowed down date range based on information found here: https://gacc.nifc.gov/swcc
remarks: A small fire burned along Arizona State Highway 87 which runs parallel to Sycamore Creek. The fire burned less than five acres and was named the Mud Fire. The burn scar is in the uplands above the creek and outside of the NEON permitted sampling area. Ash and debris runoff will likely impact the site once it rains. The area of the NEON site that would see impacts to this runoff is near the bottom of the site where there is a small tributary that only flows during large scale thunderstorms during the Monsoon season.

dateRemarks: Estimate of drought onset based on data published by the U.S. Drought Monitor on 4/26/2022.

dateRemarks: Logging occurred sometime over the winter - exact window and duration of logging unknown
remarks: Acer rubrum and Acer saccharum both heavily harvested. Some Abies balsamea also harvested but many not removed from the site leaving abundant downed trees. Apparent attempts to reduce understory competition evidenced by leveled areas of Abies balsamea and many individuals of Ostrya virginiana that were cut and left. Logging quite extensive with large amounts of slash on the ground. A list of plots with more specific logging effects: TREE_042- Evidence of logging equipment (dug up ground + deep tracks) leading up to the plot; lots of slash; bigger maples taken; smaller trees left downed. TREE_046- Lots of slash; smaller trees toppled and left; bigger logged and removed. Evidence of logging equipment present but no logging road. TREE_049- Lots of slash; smaller logged trees left behind; bigger maples logged and removed. Quadrat at 41.4 has been nearly completely covered by a fallen maple crown. TREE_050- Wooded half has many crushed trees and slash. Open part (Christmas tree farm) looks unaffected. TREE_051- Logging road through the plot; logging around the plot but not in the plot; slash around the plot but not in the plot. TREE_052- Marked for logging but was not touched. Logging around the plot but not up to plot's edge. TREE_053- Lots of slash; large maples logged and removed. TREE_054- Logging road heavily littered with slash and Abies balsamea. Heavily logged. Former thicket of Abies balsamea now very thinned out. TREE_055- Massive amounts of slash; logging road through the plot; big sections of large trees left behind; small logged trees downed and left behind; big maples mostly logged and removed. TREE_056- Lots of slash; logging 2-track to the edge of the plot; downed trees that seem run over everywhere. TREE_058- Lots of slash; many areas with downed Abies balsamea; abundant ruts and a few logging roads. Many larger trees harvested and many smaller trees downed and left on the ground.

dateRemarks: Tree fell sometime over night between 20220105-20220106
remarks: One of the largest Douglas firs in the immediate vicinity of the WREF tower was knocked down by a neighboring Hemlock somtine over night of 1/5/22-1/6/22. Because of the significance in size of this tree, some sensors readings going forward might slightly different that before it fell due to its absence.

dateRemarks: Date of rain event and peak floods. High waters persisted after event.
remarks: Heavy rain caused by a 3000 mile long atmospheric river dropped an unprecedented amount of water on a historically deep late-season snowpack causing extensive flooding and road damage throughout Yellowstone National Park. Site inaccessible. roads damaged/destroyed due to flooding. National Park Closed. Will resume sampling when able.

dateRemarks: Date reflects first observations post Yellowstone tower bear closure
remarks: Yellowstone National Park has been expanding the Frog Rock gravel pit that is adjacent to the tower airshed. The pit is being expanded towards the tower. While still out of the airshed quite a large area of previously intact soil has been disturbed and is now a flattened surface that is more prone to dust.
